{"id":"1409.6269","submitter":"Thomas McConville A","authors":"Thomas McConville","title":"Crosscut-simplicial Lattices","comments":"15 pages","journal-ref":"ORDER (2016)","doi":"10.1007/s11083-016-9409-9","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We call a lattice crosscut-simplicial if the crosscut complex of every atomic\ninterval is equal to the boundary of a simplex. Every interval of such a\nlattice is either contractible or homotopy equivalent to a sphere. Recently,\nHersh and Meszaros introduced SB-labellings and proved that if a lattice has an\nSB-labelling then it is crosscut-simplicial. Some known examples of lattices\nwith a natural SB-labelling include the join-distributive lattices, the weak\norder of a Coxeter group, and the Tamari lattice. Generalizing these three\nexamples, we prove that every meet-semidistributive lattice is\ncrosscut-simplicial, though we do not know whether all such lattices admit an\nSB-labelling. While not every crosscut-simplicial lattice is\nmeet-semidistributive, we prove that these properties are equivalent for\nchamber posets of real hyperplane arrangements.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Sep 2014 18:28:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-28"}
